<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the RSA (CMI0015)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Tms Rmn'; font-size:10pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">Written evidence from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">Royal And Sun Alliance Insurance Plc</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">(CMI0015)</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">About RSA</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">With a 300 year heritage, RSA is one of the world’s leading multinational quoted insurance groups, with the ability to write business in over 130 countries and with major operations in the UK, Scandinavia, Canada, Ireland, the Middle East and Latin America</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">RSA is the UK’s second largest commercial insurer and fourth largest personal insurer, specialising in general insurance. Our direct insurance arm, MORE TH&gt;N, is one of the UK’s top three personal motor and household insurance companies, and we also co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ver many thousands of businesses, from small enterprises through to large multinationals. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Our interest in the Paper </span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0.2pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">RSA is a major provider of motor insurance, employers’ liability insurance and public liability insurance. Under these covers, we make many payments to claimants who have suffered a personal injury as well as additional costs where they have legal represen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">tation. In addition we also provide our own ‘Before the Event’ legal expenses insurance. The types of claims we therefore deal with can be broadly categorised as follows: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Third party liability motor claims made by claimants injured in accidents involving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> RSA or MORE TH&gt;N policyholders</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Claims for personal injury or disease made by employees of employers who have an Employers’ Liability insurance policy with RSA</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Claims for personal injury or disease made by members of the public against individuals and orga</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nisations who have a Public Liability policy with RSA</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Pursuit of personal injury claims through provision of legal expenses insurance to individuals and organisations</span></li></ul><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Given RSA’s interest in this area, we welcome the opportunity to respond to this call for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> evidence. We have also worked closely on this issue with our UK trade body, the Association of British Insurers (ABI). If convenient, we would of course be happy to discuss any aspect of our response further. </span></li></ol><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> RSA support for civil justice reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> in relation to whiplash claims </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">spiraling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> costs, associated with personal injury claims</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> for whiplash</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, have been a concern for RSA and the insurance industry for some time. The existing process is costly, inefficient and slow, and does not meet the ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">eds of modern consumers. This also contributed to the increases in motor insurance pricing, and w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e have therefore supported the reforms </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">both introduced and proposed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> by the government designed to address this.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In the 4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> report, the Com</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">mittee noted that in 2012/13, the volume of motor insurance injury claims fell by 9.5%. This conclusion is incorrect based on a coding error by the DWP which was subsequently rectified</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> It is however the case that the dynamics between claims involving whiplash only injury, and those involving other elements are changing – there are a number of reasons for this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> which we expand on later.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Since the raft of reforms implemented </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in April and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> May</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, the volume of RTA claims </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">trending </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">steadily </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">upwards.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We welcome the proposed reforms in relation to medical reporting processes as it has long been our view that more rigour is required. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">However these measures in isolation will not address</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the underlying causes driving the current volume of fraudulent, exaggerated and opportunistic whiplash or RTA associated soft tissue injury claims.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">One simple achievable measure, amongst a range of further policy options, remains the increase in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Small Claims Track limit which can be implemented without prejudicing access to justice.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">If such a move was combined with the removal of Damages </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Based </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Agreements for small track personal injury claims, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">incentives for claimant lawyers to chase claims i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">n order to recover disproportionate costs would be effectively removed. It would also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">address the concerns both o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the Committee and the Government of a risk of potential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">re-emergence of a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> claims management industry to exploit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">any unrepresented claimants </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in the SCT process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The cost savings associated with an increase in the Small Claims Track was an important component part of a number of ideas to support a reduction in the cost of motor insurance following the Prime Minister’s high level summit last ye</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ar.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The limit has not changed since 1991 and we believe it should be increased.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">If the limit were to be increased to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">£5000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">it follows that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">insurers would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">be better placed to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">achieve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">one part of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">savings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">envisaged at the time of the summit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and thereby p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ass th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">se on in the form of lower</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">premiums</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We are aware of the views of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">committee around the practice of pre-medical offers to settle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> which incidentally are often accepted by claimant lawyers. Such offers are made in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> environment where currently a medical report and its associated cost do not add value to the process. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We share the Committee’s view that the Government should provide a clear statement of intent in relation to the law around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">fraudulent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">exaggeration of a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">third party </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">claim.    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Better Medical Evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Medical reporting process</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is important that the Government honour their commitment to deliver reforms to introduce independent medical panels including measures to ensure greater rigour into the proc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ess, and that they manage stakeholder consensus so as to ensure there is no slippage of the timetable.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We are concerned that the Government’s view is that accreditation should be available to all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">suitable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">practitioners.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">experience is that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">there is an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">increasing use of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">physiotherapists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">providers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">psychotherapists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> from the outset of the claim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. This enables a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">n additional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> revenue stream for claimant lawyers and is an important factor in explaining the increasing trend towards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> other forms of soft tissue and/or stress related injuries – the so called “whiplash plus”. The use of such practitioners </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">creat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> an inherent conflict for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the appropriate assessment of diagnosis and prognosis in lower value claims.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">We wou</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">ld encourage Government to tackle this through either the CPR or process change, and in addition incorporating fixed fees by Medical Reporting Organisations (MROs) reflecting the removal of any referral/marketing fees following independence of the MROs whi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">ch is an essential component of the reforms.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">t the same time however, it is important that the scope of the reforms are sufficiently broad to address </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">other elements constituting “whiplash plus” if they are to be fully effective. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">also essential that robust criteria in the form of appropriate qualifications, experience and practice forms part of the accreditation process. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s Jack Straw commented when he introduced his 10 minute Rule Bill </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, </span><spa