           </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">However </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">this practice evolved precisely because </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the current system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of medical reporting is broken. Defendants can anticipa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">te with a high degree of predictability what a medical report in the context of whiplash claims will contain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> – it does not add value to the process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In our per</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">onal lines</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> book,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> 9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">% of all pre-medical accept</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ances are with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">claimant lawyers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Therefore measures to ban the use of pre-medical offers will only deal with the symptom, not the cause. If the reforms are effective in introducing rigour not only around prognosis, but also the diagnosis of whiplash and associated soft tissue injuries in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the first place, there would be little use of pre-medical offers.     </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cash inducements to make claims</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We welcome the Government’s intention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that the ban which applies to CMCs to offer cash inducements to make a claim should be extended to apply to lawye</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">rs. The SRA has so far resisted this move</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> but needs to ban cash inducements if there is to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">be even handedness of approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in addressing all behaviours that might avoid challenging frivolous and exaggerated claims</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Law on Third Party Fraud</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We agree with the Committee that the MOJ should provide its view on limiting the right to compensation where it can be shown that a claim is grossly exaggerated. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In the Court of Appeal decision in Shah v Ul Haq Lady Justice Smith stated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e current position </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">would have to be a matter for Parliament.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Nowhere are the unsatisfactory effects of current law more apparent than in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">upreme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Court case of Summers v Fairclough where in effect the Court, did not consider that the exagg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">eration by the claimant which amounted to 90% of the value of the claim warranted the claim to be struck out but declined to give guidance as to circumstances when such an order would be given. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We remain concerned that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">hird Party fraud or exaggerati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">on continues to be treated differently from policyholder fraud – an effect which is unfair u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">pon honest policyholders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> particularly where unrecoverable cost is expended in establishing fraud.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The Small Claims track Threshold </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We feel that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Committee gave fair weight to the arguments both in favour and against increasing the Small Claims Track</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">However we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> disagree with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">conclusion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">that the limit should not be increased at this time. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The two principal objections appear to rela</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">te to access to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">justice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and potential re-emergence of claims management companies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We firmly believe that a model can be created fairly simply which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">would address </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">concerns in relation to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">“inequality of arms” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">concerns.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; f