</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The two principal areas where claimant lawyers can provide added value are around advice on legal liability and quantum.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">However in the context of whiplash </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">claims, the resolution of legal liability is usually</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">undertaken by desktop and is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">straightforward.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The introduction of judicially approved Predictable Damages software calibrated at realistic levels which reflect actual existing practice (comb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ination of mainly negotiated settlements but also including a number of judicially awarded </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">settlements) would provide transparency, certainty and protection for the claimant. There is no reason why this important recommendation by Jackson LJ, which has not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> so far been taken forward as pa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">t of his interlocking package of measures, cannot be implemented. The technology already exists and could be integrated with the development of medico-legal reporting reforms so that in effect the software is auto populated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> by medical examiners.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Provided the software has judicial approval, it would effectively </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">render </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">input of legal representation as superfluous thereby removing much of the frictional cost.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A resurgent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">claims management industry remains a legiti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">mate concern if the limit were to be increased, but such a risk could effectively be managed through a simple change to the primary legislation whereby Damages Based Agreements become unlawful for personal injury claims in the Small Claims Track (it is que</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">stionable whether they were ever intended for such use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in any event</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as long as such a measure fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">med part of a broader packa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ie provision of a wide ranging Before the Event market and protection for the unfunded claimant.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Combined with addi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tional safeguards for unrepresented claimants – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the ABI Code of Practice (with a commitment to ensure unrepresented claimants are adequately compensated), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">improved education and awareness, and the facility to be able to file paper based claims where an inj</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ured party cannot access the Portal online</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, and possibly oversight by a bespoke Ombudsman</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> – we believe access to justice can be preserved for the genuinely injured.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Small Claims Track financial limit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">for property damage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">has increased three times since the £1000 limit was set in 1991, and is now £10000 with a further increase to £15000 in contemplation. Yet the limit in respect of personal injury has not changed in that time despite the issue having been examined </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">both in 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">007 and in 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In the 12</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Edition of the Judicial College Guidelines for General Damages, there are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">six</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">categories </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in the entire publication </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">26</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> categories </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">where the recommended awards for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">pain and suffering start below £1000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nd these are pre the Simmons v</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">astle 10% uplift.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">       </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">This simple achievable measure deliver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s tangible and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">significant savings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">would assist in the delivery </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the reduction of motor insurance premiums </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">as a result of significantly lowered cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The whiplash issue and data sharing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We agree that information exchange and provision of robust data is desirable in order to continue the journey of detection and tackling of fraud.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We also support the sharing of certain relevant high </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">level data with claimant lawyers with an expectation of delivery on their responsibilities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The insurance industry which collectively funds the Insurance Fraud Enforcement Department has achieved considerable progress in the fight against fraud</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.    </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We are committed to supporting wholesale reform which enables reduction of costs through tackling fraudulent and exaggerated claims whilst ensuring that the interests of the genuine victim of an RTA accident who has suffered injury </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">are preserved. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We therefore call upon Government to deliver the full package of measures – independent medico-legal reporting with robust controls and process, and increase in the Small Claims Track – proposed in the original MOJ consultation to be imple</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">mented as soon as is feasible.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0.2pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0.2pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0.2pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">2</span></p><h1 style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 16.55pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="color:#002060; font-family:Helv; font-size:8pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h1></div></body></html>